</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,151,1538]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,1031,1057]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Small (approximately 
<quantity box="[607,723,1032,1058]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.89" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" unit="mm" value="3.89">3.89 mm</quantity>
.); head black, pronotum black with faint blue-green luster, elytra dark red-brown with light purple luster, each with large red-orange humeral area; male with all basitarsi subtriangular, apical width approximately 2/3 length; apex of penis with large, semicircular emargination (
<figureCitation box="[159,247,1152,1178]" captionStart="FIGURES 80–83" captionStartId="71.[151,269,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[215,1376,205,1926]" captionTargetId="figure-60@71.[196,1386,194,1927]" captionTargetPageId="71" captionText="FIGURES 80–83. Distal part of male aedeagus, lateral and dorsal views (scale bar = 0.5 mm). 80. F. comalensis. 81. F. dicelloposthe. 82. F.humeralis. 83. F. tibialis. (abbreviations: ae- apical emargination; al- apical lobe; ao- apical orifice)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5124679" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5124679/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 80</figureCitation>
); apical lobes large, triangular.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,151,1538]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<taxonomicName authorityName="M. S. Strother" authorityYear="1993" box="[198,399,1192,1217]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Fidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comalensis">
<emphasis box="[198,399,1192,1217]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fidia comalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is practically indistinguishable from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Strother &amp; Staines" authorityYear="2008" box="[836,1021,1192,1217]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Fidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dicelloposthe">
<emphasis box="[836,1021,1192,1217]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">F. dicelloposthe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1078,1224,1192,1217]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Fidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="humeralis">
<emphasis box="[1078,1224,1192,1217]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">F. humeralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on external characters alone, although the 
<typeStatus box="[523,626,1232,1258]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="M. S. Strother" authorityYear="1993" box="[672,830,1232,1257]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Fidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comalensis">
<emphasis box="[672,830,1232,1257]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">F. comalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the basitarsi of all legs distinctly shorter and broader than those of the males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Strother &amp; Staines" authorityYear="2008" box="[562,747,1272,1297]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Fidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dicelloposthe">
<emphasis box="[562,747,1272,1297]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">F. dicelloposthe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName box="[787,933,1272,1297]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Fidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="humeralis">
<emphasis box="[787,933,1272,1297]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">F. humeralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="M. S. Strother" authorityYear="1993" box="[1061,1220,1272,1297]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Fidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comalensis">
<emphasis box="[1061,1220,1272,1297]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">F. comalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are readily distinguished from the latter two species in having the penis apically emarginate with large, triangular apical lobes, rather than bearing a spatulate, bifurcately tipped (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Strother &amp; Staines" authorityYear="2008" box="[799,984,1352,1377]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Fidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dicelloposthe">
<emphasis box="[799,984,1352,1377]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">F. dicelloposthe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1006,1098,1352,1378]" captionStart="FIGURES 80–83" captionStartId="71.[151,269,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[215,1376,205,1926]" captionTargetId="figure-60@71.[196,1386,194,1927]" captionTargetPageId="71" captionText="FIGURES 80–83. Distal part of male aedeagus, lateral and dorsal views (scale bar = 0.5 mm). 80. F. comalensis. 81. F. dicelloposthe. 82. F.humeralis. 83. F. tibialis. (abbreviations: ae- apical emargination; al- apical lobe; ao- apical orifice)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5124679" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5124679/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 81</figureCitation>
) or small, acutely pointed (
<taxonomicName box="[161,306,1392,1417]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Fidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="humeralis">
<emphasis box="[161,306,1392,1417]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">F. humeralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation box="[324,410,1392,1418]" captionStart="FIGURES 80–83" captionStartId="71.[151,269,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[215,1376,205,1926]" captionTargetId="figure-60@71.[196,1386,194,1927]" captionTargetPageId="71" captionText="FIGURES 80–83. Distal part of male aedeagus, lateral and dorsal views (scale bar = 0.5 mm). 80. F. comalensis. 81. F. dicelloposthe. 82. F.humeralis. 83. F. tibialis. (abbreviations: ae- apical emargination; al- apical lobe; ao- apical orifice)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5124679" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5124679/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 82</figureCitation>
) apical process. The females of these three species are either indistinguishable or the females of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="M. S. Strother" authorityYear="1993" box="[281,440,1432,1457]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Fidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comalensis">
<emphasis box="[281,440,1432,1457]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">F. comalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Strother &amp; Staines" authorityYear="2008" box="[497,682,1432,1457]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Fidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dicelloposthe">
<emphasis box="[497,682,1432,1457]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">F. dicelloposthe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are unknown.
</paragraph>
